<div class="comments-body">
<p>Thanks for the pointers, Bill. The Intelligent Investor is one that's on my short list of books to read in this area.</p>

<p>My problem is that I don't have a much time to vet potential investments. Personally, I believe that my time is best spent working on things that I *am* good at, and spending time with my family. </p>

<p>The problem with picking stocks is that nobody has been able to do it consistently. If one believes in the Efficient Market Theory, then the argument is that in the long run that you can't do better than the market. I have some acquiantances who believe that they can exploit inefficiences in the market and certainly have had some short-term successes (and spectacularly so in one case). But in the end, I don't think that's a good game for me to play.</p>
<span class="comments-post">Posted by <a target="_blank" href="http://www.iunknown.com">John Lam</a> at January  4, 2004 08:34 PM</span>
</div>
<div class="comments-body">
<p>I agree with you about your best use of time. But you can also think of investing as an important hobby&mdash;you probably spend some amount of time on hobbies, right? It's also a wise use of time if you're managing investments that will materially benefit your children's future and yours as well.</p>

<p>One of the things I learned from The Millionaire Next Door (or was it The Millionaire Mind) is that investment advisors, while quite skilled and knowledgeable, don't necessarily have your best interests at heart. In other words, letting them do what they're ostensibly best at is sometimes contrary to your self-interest.</p>

<p>I just had twin daughters in October, so I'm speaking from a very hypothetical perspective. But it's one I hope to migrate towards when my girls are a bit older. In the meantime, I've got all my investments in index funds because they're as good as any other and often better in the long run.</p>
<span class="comments-post">Posted by <a target="_blank" href="http://www.bbrown.info/blogs/bblog/">Bill Brown</a> at January  5, 2004 10:54 AM</span>
